<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-04-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-04-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="245" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d245">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.77/1602</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">French Ambassador</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Translation]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">French Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-04-21">
                                    <hi rend="italic">April 21, 1917</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary of State</hi>: The Government of the
                            Republic has received recently information to the effect that the
                            railway contracts <pb facs="0354" n="188" xml:id="pg_188"/> awarded by
                            the Chinese Government to the American banked group in September last
                            included the construction of a track across Kwangsi.</p>
                        <p>My Government does not know whether the information is correct. It
                            directs me, in any event, to call your excellency’s attention to the
                            fact that such a concession would be in contravention of a formal
                            agreement made with France by the Chinese Government on September 26,
                            1914, under which we are given preference in regard to any railroad
                            built in that province which borders on Tonking.</p>
                        <p>Be pleased [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Jusserand</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>